{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὕβρις</b> [ῠ <br /> by nature, ῡ by position in <i>Epic dialect</i> etc.], ἡ, <i>genitive</i> εως [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 425, “Th.” 465 (Lyric poetry), εος [prev. author] “Pl.” 1044, 4th c.BC: Eubulus Comicus 67.9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], <i>Epic dialect</i> and <i>Ionic dialect</i> ιος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 217, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.189 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:— <b>wanton violence,</b> arising from the pride of strength or from passion, <b>insolence,</b> frequently in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey”\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], mostly of the suitors, μνηστήρων, τῶν ὕ. τε βίη τε σιδήρεον οὐρανὸν ἵκει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 15.329, 17.565; μνηστῆρες ὑπέρβιον ὕ. ἔχοντες 1.368, 4.321; λίην γὰρ ἀτάσθαλον ὕ. ἔχουσι 16.86, compare 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus “Supp.” 27.10; ὕβρει εἴξαντες 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.262, 17.431 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; θεοὶ.. ἀνθρώπων ὕβριν τε καὶ εὐνομίην ἐφορῶντες[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 487; δίκη ὑπὲρ ὕβριος ἴσχει 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus [same place], compare 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 88, “IG” 12.394 (6th c.BC), 42(1).122.98 (Epid., 4th c.BC)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; joined with ὀλιγωρίη, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.106; δυσσεβίας μὲν ὕβρις τέκος 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 533 (Lyric poetry); ἐπιθυμίας.. ἀρξάσης ἐν ἡμῖν τῇ ἀρχῇ ὕ. ἐπωνομάσθη 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 238a; in Poets frequently joined with κόρος (see. κόρος (A) 2)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: predicated of actions, ἆρ᾽ οὐχ ὕβρις τάδ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 883; ταῦτ᾽ οὐχ ὕβρις δῆτ᾽ ἐστί; 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 1299, compare “Ra.” 21, “Pl.” 886; ὕβρις τάδ᾽ ἐστί, κρείσσω δαιμόνων εἶναι θέλειν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 474 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὕβρει <b>in wantonness</b> or <b>insolence,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 881, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Apologia” 26e; ἐφ᾽ ὕβρει 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1581, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.38, “PCair.Zen.” 462.9 (3rd c.BC), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; δι᾽ ὕβριν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.42; διὰ τὴν ὕ. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 2.2.10; πρὸς ὕβριν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Alcibiades” 37, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>lust, lewdness,</b> opposed to σωφροσύνη, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 379, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.4.14. \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> of animals, <b>violence,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.189; ὕβρις ὀρθία κνωδάλων 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 10.36, compare “N.” 1.50 (see. ὑβρίζω 1.2); ἡ ἐκ τοῦ χαλινοῦ ὕ. 1st-2nd c.AD: Dio Chrysostomus Sophista 63.5. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> ={ὕβρισμα}, <b>an outrage</b> (though it is frequently difficult to separate this concrete sense from the abstract), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.203, 214; ὕβριν τεῖσαι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 24.352; ὑπὸ γυναικὸς ἄρχεσθαι ὕ. ἐσχάτη 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 111, compare 6th c.BC: Xenophanes Poeta Philosophus 1.17: sometimes, like{ὑβρίζω}, followed by a _preposition_, Ἥρας μητέρ᾽ εἰς ἐμὴν ὕβρις\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] her <b>outrage</b> towards.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ κατ᾽ Ἀργείων (-ους codices [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.AD: Priscianus Grammaticus) ὕ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 368; ἡ πρὸς τοὺς δημότας ὕ. 2nd c.AD: Herodianus Grammaticus 2.4.1: with _genitive_ objecti, ὕ. τινός\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] towards him, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 1.8.4, etc.\">Refs</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <b>wanton acts, outrages,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 146, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 247, “HF” 741, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 884a, etc.:—for ὕβριν ὑβρίζειν,compare ὑβρίζω 11.2. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>an outrage on the person,</b> especially <b>violation, rape,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 2.28, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 1.2, etc.; παίδων ὕβρεις καὶ γυναικῶν αἰσχύνας 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 4.114, compare 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 6.8.5; τὴν ὕ. τὴν εἰς τὸ ἑαυτοῦ σῶμα 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.116; τὴν τοῦ σώματος ὕβριν πεπρακώς [prev. work]188; so τὸ σῶμα ἐφ᾽ ὕβρει πεπρακώς [prev. work]29; γυναῖκας ἤγαγε δεῦρ᾽ ἐφ᾽ ὕβρει 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 19.309; γυναικῶν ὕβρεις ἢ εἰς αὑτοὺς ἢ εἰς υἱεῖς 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1373a35. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> in Law, a term covering all <b>the more serious injuries done to the person,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 20.2, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.15, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 37.33, 45.4; see especially 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21 (against Meidias); ὁ τῆς ὕβρεως νόμος [prev. work]35 (the text is given [prev. work]47); δίκη ὕβρεως ἢ πληγῶν “PHal.” 1.115 (3rd c.BC),compare “PHib.” 1.32.8 (3rd c.BC), etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> used of <b>a loss by sea,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus (see. ναυσίστονος), NT.Act.27.21. \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> as <i>masculine</i>, ={ὑβριστής}, <b>a violent, overbearing man,</b> κακῶν ῥεκτῆρα καὶ ὕβριν ἀνέρα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 191. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5196","accentedUnicode":"ὕβρις","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5195","matchingForm":"ὑβρίζω","stepTransliteration":"hubrizō","gloss":"to mistreat","_zh_tw_Gloss":"凌辱","_es_Gloss":"maltratar","_zh_Gloss":"凌辱"}],"shortDef":"insult, mistreatment; disaster, damage","mediumDef":"insult, mistreatment; disaster, damage <br /><b>insolence; shame, insult, outrage,</b> <ref='2Co.12.10'>2Cor. 12:10;</ref> <b>damage, disaster</b> by sea, <ref='Act.27.10, 21'>Acts 27:10, 21</ref>*","stepGloss":"mistreatment","stepTransliteration":"hubris","count":3,"_es_Definition":"insulto, maltrato ; daño (de barcos)","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 傲慢無禮 (經外含意)<br>2) 侮辱, 羞辱, 錯待 (林後 12:10)<br>3) 艱困, 災難, 損害","_zh_Definition":"1) 傲慢无礼 (经外含意)<br>2) 侮辱, 羞辱, 错待 (林后 12:10)<br>3) 艰困, 灾难, 损害","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"(a) xúc phạm, thương tích, phẫn nộ, tính xấc láo (b) thiệt hại, mất mát.","_zh_tw_Gloss":"傷損","_es_Gloss":"maltrato","_zh_Gloss":"伤损"}]}